LeadingAge Data-Driven Messaging

Workforce Changes & The Rise of Agency Staff

02/18/2022

All the associated data output from the following analyses are available here.

SUMMARY OF FINDINGS:

Staffing/Hours Analysis

Industry Wide (Since 04/2020):

  • 122,207 fewer active full time staff positions
  • 107,983 more contract positions. Thats about 60% growth since April, 2020.
  • 14,244 missing positions (gap between these two)
  • Contractors worked 3,652,136 more hours per month in September, 2021, than they did in April, 2020. Thats about 417 extra years of labor.
  • Its about $1.2 million more per day (assuming contractors costs just $10 more)
    • Note: A more detailed cost analysis is still in the works.

In The States (Since 04/2020):

  • Measured by total number of positions Florida, Ohio, Texas, Pennsylvania and Illinois have seen the greatest growth in the use of agency staff overall.
  • Measured by growth in hours, Florida, Delaware, Maryland, Tennessee and North Carolina lead the way, each of which have seen their total contractor hours grow by over 150% since April, 2020.

Hours By Job Type

  • Florida and Ohio suffered huge losses in both employee and contract Certified Nurse Aides, losing around 14,200 and 12,700 respectively. Over a million hours of work loss between the two. At the same time, both saw a growth of nearly 4,000 vocational nurses each.
  • Pennsylvania, Ohio, Florida, Illinois and New York lead the way in lost CNA staffing hours, with PA seeing almost 1m fewer CNA hours per month.

Attrition

  • Of the cohort of staff (2,512,262) and contractors (381,696) who were active in April, 2020, only 563,357 and 56,576 were still active in September, 2021, suggesting an attrition rate of 76% and 84% respectively.
    • From that cohort, all but one of the top 10 job classes most likely to leave were contractor positions. The exception was employee Nurse Aide in Training, which likely should be excluded.
  • The most likely contractor/agency position to leave were CNAs. Overall, 96% of the contract CNAs who were active in April, 2020 were gone by September, 2021. The most likely contractor/agency position to still be active was contract Mental Health Service Workers, 73% of whom were no longer active by September, 2021.

SOURCES & METHODS:

DATA:
  • CMS Payroll Based Journal Employee Detail Nursing Home Staffing Datasets from Q2 2020 (April 1, 2020) to Q2 2021 (September 30, 2021). Data is current to January 26, 2022.
  • CMS Payroll Based Journal, Daily Nurse Staffing and CMS Payroll Based Journal, Daily Non-Nurse Staffing. These sets were combined and used for our provider attrition analysis, which is detailed below. Both data sets are current to January 26, 2022.

NEXT STEPS:

  • We would still like to build a better estimate of the costs associated with increased use of agency/contract staff.

TECHNICAL DESCRIPTION

The following sections describe in detail the steps we took to develop this analysis and is presented in this format to help facilitate the reproduceability of the analysis by others.

HOURS ANALYSIS

CLEANING/COMBINING THE DATASETS

  • Because each of the files are on their own around 6GB in size, and because we would want to smooth out the daily variations in the data anyway, we chose to summarize all of the data by month.
  • We split the analysis into two tracks here:
    • The industry track, that doesnt break out by state.
    • The state track, that breaks all the data out by state.
  • Each of the tracks has two sub-tracks:
    • Aggregate - Only delineates between employee and contract staff
    • Staff - Breaks out the data by employee status and job function
  • Note that our analysis had a separate and additional track focused on provider and employee attrition, which is described in greater detail under Attrition Analysis below.

#note, you're making the judgment call that "month" is the widow of time you'll use. 
dataProcess = function(readFile, writeFile){
  
  data = read.csv(readFile, stringsAsFactors = FALSE, header = TRUE, check.names = FALSE)
  data$date = ymd(data$WorkDate)
  data$yearmon = format(as.Date(data$date,format="%Y-%m-%d"),"%Y-%m")
  
  industry = data %>% 
          group_by(yearmon,EMP_CTR,EMPLEE_JOB_CD_ID) %>% 
          mutate(.,avgHours=mean(WORK_HRS_NUM), totalHours = sum(WORK_HRS_NUM)) %>% 
          select(.,yearmon,EMP_CTR,EMPLEE_JOB_CD_ID,SYS_EMPLEE_ID,avgHours,totalHours) %>% distinct()
  
  industry = industry %>% 
          group_by(yearmon,EMP_CTR,EMPLEE_JOB_CD_ID) %>%
          summarise(.,total=n(),avgHours=mean(avgHours), totalHours = mean(totalHours))
  
  state = data %>% 
          group_by(yearmon,STATE,EMP_CTR,EMPLEE_JOB_CD_ID) %>% 
          mutate(.,avgHours=mean(WORK_HRS_NUM), totalHours = sum(WORK_HRS_NUM)) %>% 
          select(.,yearmon,STATE,EMP_CTR,EMPLEE_JOB_CD_ID,SYS_EMPLEE_ID,avgHours,totalHours)
  
  #have to strip things down to the "month" level. 
  state = state %>% distinct()
  
  state = state %>% 
          group_by(yearmon,STATE,EMP_CTR,EMPLEE_JOB_CD_ID) %>%
          summarise(.,total=n(),avgHours=mean(avgHours), totalHours = mean(totalHours))
  
  write.csv(industry,paste0(writeFile,"industry.csv"))
  write.csv(state,paste0(writeFile,"state.csv"))

  return(paste0("All done with ", writeFile))
}

types = c("industry_empType","state_empType")

combineTypes = function(type){
  
  path = paste0("~/Desktop/CodingProjects/la_workforce/",type)
  pbjData <- list.files(path = path,    
                      pattern = "*.csv", full.names = TRUE) %>% 
  lapply(function(i){read.csv(i,header=TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)}) 

  hmm = lapply(pbjData,function(i){as.data.frame(i)})
  hmm2 = lapply(hmm, function(i){lownames(i)})
  hmm3 = rbind.fill(hmm2)
  
  #note the name. When you do different runs, you might want to change the name here.
  write.csv(hmm3,paste0(type,"EMPall.csv"))
}

#combine all the various files into one. 
for (i in types){
  combineTypes(i)
}

DEFINE PLOTTING & OTHER FUNCTIONS



#plots that the "industry analysis" can use (doesn't break out by states)
keyPlots = function(data, subtitle, state="No"){
  
  #to avoid getting scientific notation in your axis 
  options(scipen = 100)
  
  iavg = ggplot(data,aes(yearmon,avghours,group=emp_ctr,linetype=as.factor(emp_ctr))) +
    geom_line() + 
    theme_minimal() + 
    theme(legend.position="none") +
    labs(y=NULL, x=NULL, title="Average Hours Worked Per Workday",subtitle=subtitle) +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1,size=8)) 
  
  totalWork = ggplot(data,aes(yearmon,total/1000,group=emp_ctr,linetype=as.factor(emp_ctr))) +
    geom_line() + 
    theme_minimal() + 
    theme(legend.position="none") +
    labs(y=NULL, x=NULL, title="Total Number of Active Positions",subtitle=subtitle) +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1,size=8))
  
  totalHours = ggplot(data,aes(yearmon,totalhours/1000,group=emp_ctr,linetype=as.factor(emp_ctr))) +
    geom_line() + 
    theme_minimal() + 
    theme(legend.position="none") +
    labs(y=NULL, x=NULL, title="Total Hours Worked", subtitle=subtitle) +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1,size=8))
  
  if (state == "Yes"){
    iavg = iavg + facet_wrap(~state) + theme(axis.text.x=element_blank())
    totalWork = totalWork + facet_wrap(~state) + theme(axis.text.x=element_blank()) 
    totalHours = totalHours + facet_wrap(.~state) + theme(axis.text.x=element_blank())
    plots = list(iavg,totalWork,totalHours)
  } else { plots = gridExtra::grid.arrange(totalWork,totalHours,iavg,nrow=3)}
  
  return(plots)
}


#function to handle calculating change from the first to last period 
#user should define "group_by" in the function. 
changes = function(df,state="No"){
  
  if (state=="Yes"){
    df = df %>% filter(., yearmon == min(yearmon) | yearmon == max(yearmon)) %>% group_by(.,state,emp_ctr)
  } else {df = df %>% filter(., yearmon == min(yearmon) | yearmon == max(yearmon)) %>% group_by(.,emp_ctr)}
  
  change =  df %>% summarise(., changeTotal = last(total)-first(total),
            changeTotalPercent = round(last(total)/first(total)*100,2),
            changeHours = last(totalhours)-first(totalhours), 
            changeHoursPercent = round(last(totalhours)/first(totalhours)*100,2))
  
  return(change)
  
}

changesJobName = function(df,state="No"){
  
  if (state=="Yes"){
    df = df %>% filter(., yearmon == min(yearmon) | yearmon == max(yearmon)) %>% group_by(.,state, jobName, emp_ctr)
  } else {df = df %>% filter(., yearmon == min(yearmon) | yearmon == max(yearmon)) %>% group_by(.,jobName,emp_ctr)}
  
  change =  df %>% summarise(., changeTotal = last(total)-first(total),
            changeTotalPercent = round(last(total)/first(total)*100,2),
            changeHours = last(totalhours)-first(totalhours), 
            changeHoursPercent = round(last(totalhours)/first(totalhours)*100,2))
  
  return(change)
  
}

#function to combine the data files. 
attrition = function(readFile,writeFile){

df = read.csv(readFile, stringsAsFactors = FALSE, header = TRUE, check.names = FALSE)
  adf = df %>% mutate(., date = ymd(WorkDate)) %>% 
    mutate(., yearmon = format(as.Date(date,format="%Y-%m-%d"),"%Y-%m")) %>%
    select(.,c(yearmon,STATE,SYS_EMPLEE_ID,EMP_CTR,EMPLEE_JOB_CD_ID))
  
#Using "distinct" here to get to unique combinations of the grouping variables. Couldn't do it this way in the other analysis because in the prior analysis you needed to preserve counts of hours. 
dist = adf %>% group_by(yearmon,STATE,EMP_CTR,EMPLEE_JOB_CD_ID) %>% distinct(SYS_EMPLEE_ID)

#write the file   
write.csv(dist,paste0("~/Desktop/CodingProjects/la_workforce/staffAttrition/", writeFile,".csv"))
}

#produce the simplified datasets

STAFF ATTRITION


#ANALYSIS OF THE STAFFING  DATA... 

#read in the data, and remove the extra index columns. 
staffAtr = read.csv("staffAttrAll.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE, header = TRUE)
staffAtr$x = NULL 
staffAtr$X = NULL 

#get first and last appeared using yearmon. 
staffAttr = staffAtr %>% group_by(.,sys_emplee_id) %>% mutate(.,firstSeen=min(yearmon),lastSeen=max(yearmon)) 
staffAttr$yearmon = NULL 

#make sure that every entry is unique. 
staffUnique = staffAttr %>% distinct(.,sys_emplee_id, .keep_all = TRUE)

#add interval in months to calculate how long a position was active within our time window. 
staffUnique$tenure = interval(ym(staffUnique$firstSeen),ym(staffUnique$lastSeen)) %/% months(1)

########## NOTE - ABOUT 4M UNIQUE POSITIONS BEFORE WE START FILTERING ############

filteredStaff = staffUnique %>% filter(.,lastSeen < "2021-09")

#adding duration. 
monthTenure = staffAtr %>% group_by(.,sys_emplee_id) %>% mutate(.,firstSeen=min(yearmon),lastSeen=max(yearmon)) 
monthTenure$tenure = interval(ym(monthTenure$firstSeen),ym(monthTenure$lastSeen)) %/% months(1)

#calculating monthly turnover (#employees active in the month + (#active - #who end that month))
turnover = staffAtr %>% group_by(.,sys_emplee_id) %>%
  mutate(.,firstSeen=min(yearmon),lastSeen=max(yearmon)) 

#split this set of turnover related functions up because it kept stalling my computer. 
turnover$turnover = ifelse(turnover$lastSeen==turnover$yearmon,1,0) 
turnover$tenure = interval(ym(turnover$firstSeen),ym(turnover$lastSeen)) %/% months(1)

#split into two steps because doing all in one seemed to be overloading my system. 
turnoverSummary = turnover %>% mutate(.,mt = tenure*turnover) %>% group_by(.,yearmon,emplee_job_cd_id,emp_ctr) %>%
  summarise(.,totalWorkers = n(), lostWorkers=sum(turnover), meanTenure= sum(mt)/sum(turnover))

#am wondering if I should be using "count" instead of "n_distinct" as a distinct worker could be working multiple roles. 
#everything adds up if I do "n()" relative to the grouping variables. So, will stick with that. Just have to remember, we're talking "active positions" instead of "unique workers" and there seems to be about a 3% spread between the two. 
#this 3% spread suggests that about 3% of workers work in multiple roles. 

#simple summary strips out job rolls to get to an easier count of when positions terminated. 
simpleSummary = turnover %>% mutate(.,mt = tenure*turnover) %>% 
  group_by(.,yearmon) %>% 
  summarise(.,totalWorkers = n(), lostWorkers=sum(turnover),
            meanTenure= sum(mt)/sum(turnover),
            totalTurnover = round(sum(lostWorkers)/sum(totalWorkers)*100))  



#these "first month" entries analyze only the ID numbers who were active starting in 2020-04, so you can see how that cohort fared. Surprisingly well, it seems. 

firstMonth= turnover %>% filter(.,firstSeen=="2020-04") %>% group_by(.,yearmon,emplee_job_cd_id,emp_ctr) %>%
  summarise(.,totalWorkers = n(), lostWorkers=sum(turnover), meanTenure = mean(tenure))

firstMoSimple = turnover %>% filter(.,firstSeen == "2020-04") %>% mutate(.,mt = tenure*turnover) %>% 
  group_by(.,yearmon,emp_ctr) %>% 
  summarise(.,totalWorkers = n(), lostWorkers=sum(turnover), meanTenure= sum(mt)/sum(turnover)) 

#note - I recommend filtering out 2021-09 from this analysis, as the numbers there will always add up to 100% (because 100% of any cohort that is active that month terminates at the end of our data set)

#chart on monthly attrition 
mergturn = merge(turnoverSummary,codes,by="emplee_job_cd_id")

mergeturn = mergturn %>% filter(.,yearmon != "2021-09") %>% group_by(.,yearmon,emp_ctr,jobName) %>% mutate(.,turnOver = (lostWorkers/totalWorkers)*100)


moAtt = ggplot(mergeturn,aes(yearmon,turnOver,group=emp_ctr,linetype=as.factor(emp_ctr))) +

data = read.csv("./allPayroll.csv")

#put date into familiar format
data$date = ymd(data$workdate)

#note - One entry shows up with a workdate of 0. Is provnum 285294. All data from this entry is missing. You're filtering it out to make sure it doesn't become a problem down the road. 

data = data %>% filter(., workdate != "0")

#drop X column 
data$X = NULL 

#just taking provider ID, state, and date 
justProviders = data %>% select(.,c("date","state","provnum"))
justProviders$yearmon = format(as.Date(justProviders$date,format="%Y-%m-%d"),"%Y-%m")
justProviders = justProviders %>% group_by(.,provnum) %>% summarise(.,firstAppear=min(yearmon),lastAppear=max(yearmon))

#make list of providers who last appeared in any month other than September, 2021.
lostProviders = justProviders %>% filter(.,lastAppear != "2021-09")

#count the total of last providers by month
lostP_monTotal = lostProviders %>% group_by(.,lastAppear) %>% summarise(.,monthlyTotal = n())

#build a list with provider info 
providers = data %>% select(.,c(provnum,provname,city,state,mdscensus)) %>% group_by(provnum,city,state,provname) %>% summarise(.,avgCensus=mean(mdscensus),maxCensus=max(mdscensus),lastCensus = last(mdscensus))


#list of providers with some sort of name change or variance in name/location 
nameChange = providers %>% ungroup() %>% select(.,provnum) %>% group_by(.,provnum) %>% summarise(., count=n()) %>% filter(.,count>1)

#filter out name changes to avoid duplicates 
providers = merge(providers,nameChange,by="provnum",all.x=TRUE)

#merge with list of closures 

#build a list of missing providers
lpList = merge(lostProviders,providers,by="provnum",all.x=TRUE)

#check missing provider list against name changes. 
finalList = lpList %>% distinct(provnum, .keep_all = TRUE)
finalList$count = NULL

#lost providers by state 
lostProState = finalList %>% group_by(.,state) %>% summarize(.,count=n())

#check to see if LeadingAge Member 
#load data 
ownData = read.csv("/Users/essbie/Desktop/CodingProjects/r_nursing\ home\ compare/laMatched.csv",stringsAsFactors = FALSE,header = TRUE)
